<p>Multiple epiphyseal dysplasia is a clinically and genetically heterogeneous skeletal disorder characterized by joint pain and stiffness, mild short stature, and degenerative joint disease. Onset of the disorder is usually in childhood (summary by Jackson et al., 2010).</p>

<p>For a general phenotypic description and a discussion of genetic heterogeneity of EDM, see EDM1.</p>

<p>[Jackson, G. C., Marcus-Soekarman, D., Stolte-Dijkstra, I., Verrips, A., Taylor, J. A., Briggs, M. D. Type IX collagen gene mutations can result in multiple epiphyseal dysplasia that is associated with osteochondritis dissecans and a mild myopathy. Am. J. Med. Genet. 152A: 863-869, 2010.]<br/></p>